idh</b> ‘son of <i>Gothradh</i>’, from a Gaelic form of the personal name   Godfrey  . See also   McGorry  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Corraidh</b>, ‘son of <i>Corradh</i>’, a personal name from the adjective <i>corr</i> ‘pointed’ or <i>carr</i> ‘spear’."]},{"name":"Currie","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Currie in Midlothian, first recorded in this form in 1230. It is derived from Gaelic <i>curraigh</i>, dative case of <i>currach</i> ‘wet plain, marsh’.","Scottish: habitational name from Corrie in Dumfriesshire or another place so named (see   Corrie  ).","Scottish form of Irish   Curry   or, in Arran, an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Mhuirich</b> (see   McMurray  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Corrie was born in 1378, in Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, David Currie, was 20 and his mother, Lady Herries, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Helene Corrie. He died in 1444, in Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1378–1444":"1378–1444","1375–1445":"1375–1445","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1358–1378":"1358–1378","1358–1444":"1358–1444","1358":"1358","1445":"1445","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1444":"1444","1375":"1375","1460":"1460","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, 